<answer> The clonal ecotype model, as promoted by the Open Biomedical Ontology (OBO) Foundry, provides a framework to name and define the types, properties, and relationships of entities in the biomedical domain. The CL was established in 2005 to provide a standard reference nomenclature for in vivo cell types, initially those identified in specific tissues from experiments in humans and different model organisms. The semantic hierarchy of CL is mainly constructed using two core relations: is_a and derives_from. Mao et al. proposed a major revision to the CL, using dendritic cells as the driving biological use case in which the expression of specific marker proteins on the cell surface (e.g., receptor proteins) or internally (e.g., transcription factors) would be used as the main difference for the asserted hierarchy. Cohan et al. applied this approach, first to cell types of the hematopoietic system and then later to the full CL. (bbox_2d: (695, 102, 791, 488), Image_index: 1)
</answer>
